{HEADER:HUNGER}

Stationeers get hungry eventually, but not all food is created equal. Also, your hunger rate varies depending on settings and difficulty. Eating will only consume that part of an item adequate to restoring your hunger to 100%.

Stationeers receive supplies of food such as {LINK:Agrizero;Agrizero} {THING:ItemCerealBar} in their lander upon arriving on a new world. When these are exhausted, you must find new sources of sustenance - such as growing your own, from the seeds supplied, or contacting a {LINK:TradingPage;Trader}. 

{HEADER:NUTRITION}

Eating raw ingredients will satisfy hunger less than meals, ie will replace a smaller proportion of your hunger. The basic elements of food are created using {LINK:OrganicPage;hydroponics} systems. These can be processed into recipe ingredients using the {THING:ApplianceReagentProcessor}, then turned into meals using a {THING:ApplianceMicrowave} or {THING:StructureAutomatedOven}.

Your hunger rate can be adjusted set in the main settings menu by adjusting the Hunger/Hydration rate slider in the settings. Note that the hunger slider also governs your {LINK:HydrationPage;Thirst}.

To survive on alien worlds, the {LINK:ODA;ODA} expects all {LINK:Stationeers;Stationeers} to set up viable {LINK:OrganicPage;hydroponic} systems, or contact registered local resource {LINK:TradingPage;traders}.

{HEADER:SETTING UP}

When setting up your hydroponic system, you will need {LINK:OrganicPage;seeds}. Alternatively, you can plant the food itself.

Common Stationeer hydroponic equipment includes:

- {THING:DynamicHydroponics}
- {THING:ItemHydroponicTray}
- {THING:ItemKitHydroponicStation}
- {THING:StructureHarvie}

All hydroponics systems require water, sunlight and the correct gas mixture - plants require {GAS:CarbonDioxide} and produce oxygen (except for {THING:ItemAlienMushroom}). PLants will not grow in the wrong atmosphere. If plants do not have enough light, you will need to build a {THING:StructureGrowLight}.

Your system will depend on available resources and time, but a well-designed farming system can be almost fully automated given sufficient time and resources.

{HEADER:HARVESTING}

Most plants have several growth stages. The first stages are the plant growing through its lifecycle. During the third phase, seeds may be harvested from the plant. In the fourth phase, the plant will yield fruit. After that, unless cleared, the plant will die.

{HEADER:FERTILIZER}

Fertilizer alters plant growth processes, and is created by the {THING:PortableComposter} and the {THING:StructureAdvancedComposter} using {LINK:OrganicPage;organic} matter.

Fertilizer's affects depend on its ingredients:

- {LINK:OrganicPage;Food} increases individual PLANT YIELD by up to 3 items
- {THING:DecayedFood} increases plant GROWTH SPEED up to 3 times
- {THING:ItemBiomass} increases the NUMBER OF GROWTH CYCLES the fertilizer lasts for to a maximum of 5

The effect of these ingredients depends on their respective proportions in the composter when processing is activated. Fertilizer is produced at a 1:3 ratio of fertilizer to ingredients. When processing, {GAS:Nitrogen} and {GAS:Volatiles} is released, as well a small amount of heat.
